{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"630bbec5-1dd7-45f6-8a96-8795202d220f","content":"With **MSTest 3.8.2**, use **constructor injection** for `TestContext` and sync init, and `[TestInitialize]` for async init:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests\n{\n    private readonly HttpClient _client;\n\n    public TestContext TestContext { get; }\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        // Constructor: sync init + TestContext injection\n        TestContext = testContext;\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task SetupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async initialization runs before each test\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        TestContext.WriteLine(\"Running test\");\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_client);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points (MSTest v3):**\n- **`TestContext`** — inject via constructor parameter; no more `static` property hack.\n- **Sync init** — use the constructor.\n- **Async init** — use `[TestInitialize] async Task` (constructors can't be async).\n- Execution order: Constructor → `TestInitialize` → Test → `TestCleanup`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7b0f8012-6cc3-4995-a14d-8323943d1c63","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"They're using MSTest 3.8.2 on .NET 9. In MSTest v3, the recommended way to handle initialization is:\n\n1. **TestContext injection**: In MSTest v3, `TestContext` can be injected via the constructor (no more need for the static property pattern). Actually, let me be more precise. In MSTest 3.x, the recommended approach is to use constructor injection for `TestContext`.\n\n2. **Synchronous initialization**: Use the constructor or `[TestInitialize]` method.\n\n3. **Asynchronous initialization**: Use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method.\n\nActually, in MSTest 3.x, the `TestContext` can be set via constructor injection. \n\nThe old static property with `[ClassInitialize]` pattern is gone—now you just pass `TestContext` directly into the constructor. For async setup, `[TestInitialize]` can be async, while the constructor handles synchronous initialization.","outputTokens":564,"requestId":"5C33:1ECD:1727F3:1DC3CC:69F55301"},"id":"95017783-21f7-4088-80fe-12a63b221d17","timestamp":"2026-05-02T01:27:40.950Z","parentId":"bef9df3d-9535-4927-aeeb-c52aa2d8ae69"}
